ename probably derives from the late Old English personal name <i>Lothen</i> (genitive <i>Lothenes</i>), from Old Norse <i>Lothinn</i>, + Old English <i>dæl</i> ‘valley’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Lansdale was born about 1345, in England, his father, John de Lansdall, was 31 and his mother, Mrs. John de Lansdall, was 27. He had at least 1 daughter with Catherine Herman. He died about 1386, in England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"about 1345–about 1386":"umbes 1345–umbes 1386","1345–1386":"1345–1386","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1398":"umbes1375–1398","1315–1360":"1315–1360","1319–Female":"1319–Surnud","1315":"1315","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1398":"1398","1375":"umbes 1375","1386":"1386","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1395":"1395","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","about 1386":"umbes 1386","1319":"1319","England":"England","Kent, Kent, England":"Kent, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1345–about 1386":"noin 1345–noin 1386","1345–1386":"1345–1386","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1375–1398":"